'''Dominik Hašek''' ([[International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]] {{IPA|['dominɪk 'haʃɛk]}}) (born [[January 29]], [[1965]], in [[Pardubice]], [[Czechoslovakia]]) is a professional [[National Hockey League]] [[goaltender]] for the [[Detroit Red Wings]]. In his 15-season NHL career, he has also played for the [[Chicago Blackhawks]], [[Buffalo Sabres]] and the [[Ottawa Senators]]. During his years in Buffalo, he became one of the league's finest goaltenders, earning him the nickname "The Dominator." His strong play is credited for bringing European goaltenders into a league where the position was once widely dominated by North Americans.<ref name = "return">{{cite news
| last = Samuelson
| first = Karl
| url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCM/is_1_32/ai_107896442
| title = The return of the dominator: after taking a year off to charge his batteries, Dominik Hasek is back in goal for Detroit and ready to win another Cup
| publisher = [[Hockey Digest]]
| date = 2003-11-01
| accessdate = 2007-01-09}}</ref>

Hašek has been one of the league's most successful goaltenders over the past decade and a half. In an eight season span from [[1992-93 NHL season|1993]] to [[2000-01 NHL season|2001]] he won six [[Vezina Trophy|Vezina Trophies]], and in 1998 he became the first goaltender to win consecutive [[Hart Memorial Trophy|Hart Trophies]].<ref name = "azhockey">{{cite web
| url = http://www.azhockey.com/Ha.htm
| title = A to Z Encyclopedia of Ice Hockey
| accessdate = 2007-01-09}}</ref>
During the [[Ice hockey at the 1998 Winter Olympics|1998 Winter Olympics]] in [[Nagano]], [[Japan]], he led the [[Czech national ice hockey team]] to its first Olympic gold medal, which transformed him into one of the most popular figures in the Czech Republic,<ref name="Popularity">
{{cite web
  | title = Q&A: Czech hockey goalie Dominik Hasek
  | publisher = Canadian Broadcasting Corporation
  | date = 2006-02-03
  | url = http://www.cbc.ca/olympics/stories/indepth.shtml?/story/olympics/national/2006/02/01/Sports/hasek-qa060201.html
  | accessdate = 2006-08-07 }}</ref> and prompted hockey legend [[Wayne Gretzky]] to call him "the best player in the game."<ref name="passion">{{cite news
| last = Wigge
| first = Larry
| title = Passionate or passionless? It's a harbinger of spring - whether certain key players are playing with the passion and intensity needed for success in the Stanley Cup playoffs - NHL Insider - Column
| url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1208/is_n12_v222/ai_20425448
| date = 1998-03-23
| accessdate = 2007-04-04}}
</ref> In [[2001-02 NHL season|2002]], Hašek became the first European starting goaltender to win the [[Stanley Cup]] when he led the Red Wings to a championship.<ref>{{cite news
| title = Lidstrom becomes first European to win Conn Smythe Trophy
| url = http://www.iihf.com/news/iihfpr3402.htm
| publisher = IIHF
| date = 2002-06-14
| accessdate = 2007-04-26}}</ref>

Hašek is considered a very unorthodox goaltender, with a distinct play style that has labeled him as a "flopper."<ref name="MainBio">{{cite web|url=http://hockeygoalies.org/bio/hasek.html|title=Dominik Hasek (1990-present)|publisher=hockeygoalies.org|accessdate=2007-04-24|year=2007}}</ref> He is best known for his excellent concentration, his tremendous foot speed and his immense flexibility, all of which help him make extremely difficult saves. He will often drop his stick and grab a loose puck with his blocker hand rather than use the conventional [[Glove (hockey)|trapper]], and is generally weak with his stick play.<ref name="MainBio"/>

Hasek is regarded as a future Hall of Famer by those in the hockey world.<ref>{{cite news
| url = http://www.cbc.ca/story/sports/national/2006/07/31/dominik-hasek-detroit.html
| title = Dominik Hasek returns to Detroit | publisher = Canadian Press
| date = 2006-07-31}}</ref> He is the oldest active goalie in the NHL at 42, and the second oldest active player in the league after Red Wings teammate [[Chris Chelios]], who is 45. 

==Early Life==
In his native [[Czechoslovak Socialist Republic|Czechoslovakia]], Hašek started playing hockey at a very young age. His competitive goaltending career began at the age of six, as he explains:<ref name="flex">{{cite news
| last = Wigge
| first = Larry
| title = The dominator - goalie Dominik Hasek
| url = http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1208/is_n45_v219/ai_17519444
| publisher = The Sporting News
| date = 1995-11-06
| accessdate = 2006-01-22}}</ref>

{{cquote|They held a tryout for 6-year-old boys and my father took me there. I didn't even have real skates. I had those blades that you screwed onto the soles of your shoes, but I was tall, and the 9-year-olds didn't have a goalie, so they put me in with them.}} 

At the age of 16, Hašek made the move to the top level of Czech hockey, playing for his home team in the Czech league's First Division. After moving up the ranks and eventually playing for the Czechoslovakian National team, Hašek thought he was ready for the NHL. He was drafted by the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] in [[1983 NHL Entry Draft|1983]], and despite being a very talented player, he was selected in the 10th round, 199th overall. This was mainly due to the unwillingness of NHL teams to draft players from behind the [[Iron Curtain]], as players' countries often barred them from playing in the NHL, or the players themselves preferred not to go. It would be several months before Hašek would find out that he was even drafted.<ref name="draft">{{cite web|url=http://www.legendsofhockey.net:8080/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/SearchPlayer.jsp?player=18282|title=Dominik Hasek|publisher=legendsofhockey.net|accessdate=2006-08-05}}</ref>

From that point up until 1990, Hašek played in his native Czechoslovakia for the [[Czechoslovak Extraliga]] teams [[HC Pardubice]] and [[HC Jihlava]]. He also played parts of two seasons in the [[International Hockey League|IHL]] with the [[Indianapolis Ice]]. He was named the [[Golden Hockey Stick (Czechoslovakia)|top ice hockey player]] in Czechoslovakia in 1987, 1989, and 1990, along with being named Czechoslovakian Goaltender of the Year from 1986 through 1990.<ref>[http://tsn.ca/nhl/teams/players/bio/?id=126&hubname=nhl-red_wings TSN.ca player profile]</ref> After [[History of the Soviet Union (1985-1991)|communist rule ended]] in 1991, the borders of the Soviet Union opened, allowing him to emigrate to the United States with aspirations of playing in the NHL.<ref name="draft"/> His debut with the Blackhawks finally came in the [[1990-91 NHL season|1990-91 season]], eight years after the 1983 NHL Entry Draft.

==NHL career==
In Chicago, Hašek spent time as the backup to [[Ed Belfour]], and only played 25 games over two seasons with the Blackhawks. He made his NHL debut on November 6, 1990 in a game against the [[Hartford Whalers]] and wore the number 31. He would record his first shutout against the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] later that year.

On [[August 7]], [[1992]], Hašek was traded to the [[Buffalo Sabres]] for goalie [[Stephane Beauregard]] and future considerations, which later materialized into a draft pick used to obtain [[Eric Daze]]. In Buffalo, wearing number 39, he was initially the backup goaltender, first playing behind [[Tom Draper]] and then [[Grant Fuhr]]. When Fuhr was injured partway through the season, Hašek was elevated to starter, where he displayed his talent and began to develop into a top tier goaltender.

In [[1993-94 NHL season|1994]], Hašek won his first [[Vezina Trophy]], and he shared the [[William M. Jennings Trophy]] with teammate Grant Fuhr. Hašek played 58 games with a league-best 1.95 [[Goals against average|GAA]], seven shutouts, and a .930 [[save percentage]]. He followed this feat by again winning the Vezina Trophy in [[1994-95 NHL season|1995]].

====Buffalo (1996-1998)====
[[Image:VezinaHasek.jpg|thumb|1998: Dominik Hasek with the Vezina Trophy, left, and [[Hart Trophy]], right. Hasek also won the [[Lester B. Pearson Award]] that year. He defended those victories from [[1996-97 NHL season|the previous year]].]]

The regular season success of the Sabres in [[1996-97 NHL season|1996-97]] was overshadowed by several conflicts, including one between Hašek and then-head coach [[Ted Nolan]], which contributed to a clique-like atmosphere in the franchise.<ref name="rattling">{{cite news
| last = Wigge
| first = Larry
| title = Sabres are rattling over Hasek's Nolan comments - Buffalo goalie Dominik Hasek, former coach Ted Nolan - NHL Report - Column
| url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1208/is_n37_v221/ai_19757655
| publisher = The Sporting News
| date = 1997-09-15
| accessdate = 2007-04-04}}</ref>
Tensions were high for most of the season, and after the [[Ottawa Senators]] scored on Hašek in game three of the first round of the playoffs, he was replaced by [[Steve Shields (hockey player)|Steve Shields]]. Hašek claimed he felt his knee pop, and the team doctor pronounced him day-to-day. Being integral to the Sabres' Cup run, the media (and some teammates) speculated that Hašek was using his injury to bail out on the team.<ref name="rattling"/> ''Buffalo News'' columnist [[Jim Kelley]] wrote a column that night that appeared in the following day's newspaper that detailed Hašek's injury and the conflict with Nolan, and accused Hašek of having poor mental toughness.<ref name="kelley">{{cite news
| last = Don
| first = Brennan
| title = Dominator feels the love
| url = http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Columnists/Brennan/2006/02/05/1427127-sun.html
| accessdate = 2007-04-04}}</ref> After the Senators won game five, Kelley approached Hašek for an interview, and Hašek attacked Kelley.<ref name="kelley"/> He received a three-game suspension and a $10,000 (US) fine. Shields starred as the Sabres rallied to win the series against Ottawa. However, Hašek claimed his knee was still injured throughout the next series against the [[Philadelphia Flyers]], which saw the Sabres' elimination in five games.

Though General Manager [[John Muckler]] was named "Executive of the Year", he was fired for his constant feuding with Nolan. Hašek, who sided with Muckler, stated in an interview during the 1997 NHL Awards Ceremony that it would be better of Nolan was not rehired.<ref>{{cite news
| last = Smith
| first = Jim
| title = Buffalo in love with `Dominator'
| url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4196/is_19980524/ai_n10427406
| publisher = The Milwaukee Journal Sentinel
| date = 1998-05-24
| accessdate = 2007-04-04}}</ref>
Despite winning the [[Jack Adams Award]] as top coach, Nolan was only offered a one-year contract extension by replacement GM [[Darcy Regier]], which he rejected under the grounds that it was too short. He did not return the following season. Nolan was a popular coach, and many fans were upset by Hašek's alleged actions to get rid of Nolan.<ref>{{cite news
| last = Crouse
| first = Karen
| title = Solving Hasek not an easy task
| url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4196/is_19980110/ai_n10388519
| publisher = The Milkwaukee Journal Sentinel
| date = 1998-01-10
| accessdate = 2007-04-04}}</ref>
For the first six weeks of the next season he was booed so vigorously that arena workers would play tapes of a crowd cheering to help balance it out.<ref>{{cite news
| last = Gleason
| first = Bucky
| title = Hasek awakens from dream run
| url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4196/is_19980308/ai_n10410586
| publisher = The Milkwaukee Journal Sentinel
| date = 1998-03-08
| accessdate = 2007-04-04}}</ref>
As the season progressed, Hašek played well and won back many fans; he again won the Vezina Trophy, as well as the [[Lester B. Pearson Award]] and the [[Hart Trophy]]. At the time, he was only the second goalie to ever win the Hart, along with [[Jacques Plante]].

Hasek played a career high 72 games in the [[1997-98 NHL season|1997-98 season]], and set a team record with 13 shutouts. Six of these shutouts came in December, which tied the all-time NHL record for most in one month.<ref name="HockeydCentral">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydraftcentral.com/1983/83199.html|title=Dominik Hasek Bio at HockeyDraftCentral|publisher=hockeydraftcentral.com|accessdate=2007-04-24|year=2007}}</ref> He again won the Lester B. Pearson Award, the Hart Trophy, and the Vezina Trophy, becoming the first goalie in NHL history to win the Hart twice. He donated the $10,000 prize money after winning the Pearson Award in 1998 to the ''Variety Club of Buffalo''.<ref name="HockeydCentral"/>

====1999 Stanley Cup Finals====
[[Image:Hasek hull goal.jpg|right|thumb|An overhead shot of Hull's controversial goal]]

In [[1998-99 NHL season|1999]], Hašek notched a career best 1.87 GAA and .937 save percentage, easily capturing him his third consecutive Vezina. He also finished runner-up for the Hart and Pearson trophies. Though the Sabres did not have a stellar regular season and finished with the seventh seed in the [[Eastern Conference (NHL)|Eastern Conference]], they defeated the [[Ottawa Senators]], [[Boston Bruins]], and [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] in the playoffs en route to a best-of-seven Stanley Cup Final against the [[Presidents' Trophy]]-winning [[Dallas Stars]]. The Sabres eventually lost the series four games to two, with the decisive sixth game being one of the longest Stanley Cup playoff games in NHL history. Hašek and [[Ed Belfour]] made 50 and 53 saves, respectively, in a sudden-death [[Overtime (ice hockey)|triple-overtime]] duel that only ended when [[Brett Hull]] scored a controversial Cup-winning goal with his foot in the crease. <ref name = "hull goal">{{cite news
| title = 37: Brett Hull's controversial Stanley Cup goal
| url = http://www.tsn.ca/20/news_story/?ID=104962&hubname=
| date = 2004-11-17
| accessdate = 2007-01-22}}</ref> The following season, the league removed the crease rule.

After the season ended, Hašek contemplated retirement due to a combination of injuries and a desire to become more involved in his family life.<ref name="wp retire">{{cite news
| last = La Canfora 
| first = Jason
| title = The Dominator Down to One Season and Out
| url = http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/nhl/longterm/1999/preview/articles/hasek1.htm
| publisher = Washington Post
| date = 1999-10-1
| accessdate = 2006-11-06}}
</ref> His initial announcement that he was considering quitting hockey stunned many of his teammates, particularly [[Mike Peca]] and [[Jason Woolley]].<ref name="wp retire"/>

====Final years with Buffalo (1999-2001)====

Due to persistent injuries, Hašek's [[1999-2000 NHL season|1999-00 season]] was comparatively poor, and, for the first time in several years, he failed to win a major NHL award. Though he recovered in time for the playoffs, the Sabres were eliminated in the first round after five games against the Philadelphia Flyers.

The [[2000-01 NHL season|2000-01 season]] would be Hašek's final year in Buffalo, and would see him winning the Vezina Trophy for the sixth time, the most of any goaltender in the modern era. He also won his second [[William M. Jennings Trophy]]. The Sabres were again matched up with Philadelphia in the first round, where Hašek outplayed his Czech compatriot and 1998 Olympic back-up [[Roman Cechmanek]].  Hašek led the Sabres to an 8-0 blanking of the Flyers in the clinching sixth game. In the second round, the Sabres played a dramatic seven-game series against [[Mario Lemieux]]'s [[Pittsburgh Penguins]], which culminated with the Penguins winning the final game in overtime.

====Detroit and Ottawa (2001-present)====
Prior to the start of [[2001-02 NHL season|the next season]], Hašek was traded to the [[Detroit Red Wings]] in an attempt to lower the Sabres' payroll and to send Hašek to a more competitive team.<ref name = "return"/> He was dealt for [[Vyacheslav Kozlov]], a first round selection in the [[2002 NHL Entry Draft]] (which eventually became the draft pick of [[Jim Slater (ice hockey)|Jim Slater]]), and future considerations. 

During his first season with Detroit, Hašek posted a career high 41 wins with just 15 losses, helping the Red Wings earn the President's Trophy with the league's best record. In the playoffs, he led the Wings past the [[Vancouver Canucks]], the [[St. Louis Blues]], the [[Colorado Avalanche]] and eventually the [[Carolina Hurricanes]] in the finals to win the [[Stanley Cup]]. In the finals, he became the first goalie to be awarded an assist on an overtime game-winning goal in the post-season after passing the puck to Wings captain [[Steve Yzerman]], who then assisted [[Fredrik Olausson]] in scoring the final goal. He also claimed the record for most shutouts in a post-season with six, though [[Martin Brodeur]] of the [[New Jersey Devils]] immediately broke the record in [[2002-03 NHL season|2003]].

That summer Hašek officially announced his retirement so he could spend time with his family and other hobbies, and claimed that his career was complete.<ref name="comeback">
{{cite news
| title = Hasek contemplates NHL comeback
| url = http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2003/06/24/hasek030623.html
| date = 2003-06-24
| accessdate = 2007-01-24}}</ref>
After Detroit's first round loss to the [[Anaheim Ducks|Mighty Ducks of Anaheim]] in the [[2002-03 NHL season|following season]], he announced his desire to play again. However, the Red Wings had two years left on [[Curtis Joseph]]'s three-year $24 million contract, which had a no-trade clause. Detroit was also under pressure with the knowledge that the rival [[Colorado Avalanche]] would be looking for a goalie to replace [[Patrick Roy]] after his retirement.<ref name="comeback"/> With [[Manny Legacé]] also on the Wings' roster, Detroit now had three potential starting goalies.

The [[2003-04 NHL season|2003-04 season]] was problematic for Hašek, as he injured his groin after playing just 14 games. Early into the 2004 year on [[January 9]], he and the team agreed he should rest his injury for two to four weeks. Hašek told general manager [[Ken Holland]] that he would not accept any pay while he was injured; he did not make his refusal public at the time. On [[February 10]], he announced that he was not going to continue to play that season, surprising the Red Wings management.<ref>
{{cite news
| last = Allen
| first = Kevin
| title = Hasek's decision to sit out season ruffles Red Wings
| url = http://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/nhl/wings/2004-02-10-hasek-out_x.htm
| date = 2004-02-10
| accessdate = 2007-01-24}}</ref> He eventually revealed that he refused $3 million of his $6 million salary.<ref>{{cite news
| last = Householder
| first = Mike
| title = Hasek refuses about $3 million of salary while out with injury
| url = http://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/nhl/wings/2004-03-12-hasek-salary_x.htm
| date = 2004-03-12
| accessdate = 2007-01-22}}</ref> In April 2004, he underwent groin surgery in [[Prague]], and returned to his hometown of [[Pardubice]] to recuperate.  
[[Image:Hasekpractice.jpg|250px|left|thumb|Hašek in warm-up before a game against the [[Los Angeles Kings]] on March 9, 2007.]]
After his contract with the Wings expired, Hašek announced his intention to play for a [[Stanley Cup]] contender, and specifically named the [[Ottawa Senators]] as a possibility.<ref>{{cite news
| last = Karl
| first = Samuelson
| title = A calculated gamble: the Senators' are banking on Dominik Hasek to help push them to the Stanley Cup Finals
| url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCM/is_1_33/ai_n6355249
| publisher = Hockey Digest
| date = November-December 2004
| accessdate = 2007-04-22}}</ref> On [[July 6]], [[2004]], the Senators signed Hašek to a one-year deal, after trading [[Patrick Lalime]] to the [[St. Louis Blues (hockey)|St. Louis Blues]] 

Hasek played increasingly well for the Senators up until the [[2006 Winter Olympics]]. During the season, he reached 300 career wins, and his GAA and save percentage were the second-best in the league. However, at the Olympics, he injured his right [[Adductor muscles of the hip|adductor muscle]] making a save in the first match against [[Germany at the 2006 Winter Olympics#Ice hockey|Germany]].<ref>{{cite news
| title = Hasek sidelined by groin injury
| url = http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/news_story/?ID=155130&hubname=
| publisher = TSN
| date = 2006-02-16
| accessdate = 2007-01-24}}</ref>
Despite the loss, the [[Czech Republic at the 2006 Winter Olympics#Ice hockey|Czech Republic]] finished in third place, and Hašek was awarded the [[bronze medal]] after playing just 9 minutes and 25 seconds.

Hašek's injury caused him to miss the rest of the regular season and post-season despite several rumours that he would return in time for [[2006 Stanley Cup Playoffs|the playoffs]]. Hašek said that if he were to be re-signed, he would play for a base salary of just $500,000 with bonuses.<ref>{{cite news
| last = Garrioch 
| first = Bruce
| title = Hasek willing to play for a base salary of $500,000
| url = http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/NHL/Draft/2006/06/24/1651041-sun.html
| publisher = Ottawa Sun
| accessdate = 2007-01-24}}</ref>
After the Senators were eliminated, they opted not to re-sign Hašek. On [[July 31]], [[2006]], at the age of 41, Hašek joined the Red Wings for the third time in his career. He signed a one-year $750,000 US contract, with added bonuses if the team succeeds in the playoffs. On [[November 14]]th, [[2006]], the [[Vancouver Canucks]] scored on Hašek and broke his personal best shutout streak of 181 minutes, 17 seconds.<ref>{{cite web
| title = Hasek sets career-best NHL shutout streak
| url = http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2006/11/15/sports/NA_SPT_HKY_NHL_Red_Wings_Hasek.php
| date = 2006-11-15
| access date = 2006-11-15
}}
</ref>

Midway through the regular season, the team announced that in order to avoid injury and to preserve Hasek for the playoffs, Hašek would not play on consecutive nights.<ref>{{cite news
| last = Sharp
| first = Drew
| title = THE REJUVENATOR: Hasek plays like his old self
| url = http://www.freep.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070422/COL08/704220597/1081
| publisher = Detroit Free Press
| date = 2007-04-22
| accessdate = 2007-04-22}}</ref> He played on consecutive nights for the first time of the season on [[April 21]] and [[April 22|22]] against the [[Calgary Flames]] in games 5 and 6 of the Eastern Conference Quarterfinals. He would go on to win both games and help Detroit win the series 4 games to 2 after [[Johan Franzen]] scored the series-winning goal in double-overtime.

==International play==
[[Image:0222 hockey2.jpg|thumb|199px|left|Hašek in goal at the gold medal game against Russia in the 1998 Winter Olympics. In a 20 save performance he earned a shutout in a 1-0 victory]]
