==Legacy==
===Milestones===
Hašek won his 300th National Hockey League game on [[October 15]], [[2005]], in a 5-1 home victory with the [[Ottawa Senators]] over the [[Boston Bruins]]. He stopped 34 of 35 shots in the win, and was holding a shutout until Bruins forward [[Pat Leahy (ice hockey)|Pat Leahy]] jammed a loose puck under him three minutes into the third period. Hasek became the twenty-second goaltender to reach this milestone.<ref name="MainBio"/> He is the oldest goaltender in NHL history to post a 30-win season, and was the first goaltender to ever win the [[Lester B. Pearson Award]] in [[1996-97 NHL season|1997]] for most outstanding player in the entire league. He is also the only goaltender to win the [[Hart Trophy]] twice for Most Valuable Player, and is only one [[Vezina Trophy]] away from tying [[Jacques Plante]]'s total of seven for most all-time.

===Records===
In nine seasons with the Buffalo Sabres, Hašek acquired over 25 franchise records, including most all-time games played, wins, shutouts and lowest goals aganst average.<ref name="HockeydCentral"/> He also holds the Sabres' record for most shutouts in a single season with 13 in [[1997-98 NHL season|1997-98]], and lowest goals against average in a single season with a total of 1.87 in [[1998-99 NHL season|1998-99]]. During the Detroit Red Wings' championship run in [[2001-02 NHL season|2002]], Hašek set franchise records for most games played, minutes played, wins and shutouts in a playoff year. He is also on several notable NHL records lists:

<div style="float:left; margin-right:1.5em;">
{{h4|All-time}}
* 1st place — Most games played by a European<br>born goaltender (694)
* 7th place — Most shutouts (76)
* 8th place — Lowest goals against average (2.21)
* 14th place — Most wins (362)
* 4th place — Most wins of all active players
* 3rd place — Most shutouts of all active players
</div><div style="float:left; margin-right:3.5em;">
{{h4|Regular Season}}
* Longest shutout streak (181 minutes, 17 seconds)
* Most saves in a shutout victory (42)<ref name="HockeydCentral"/>
* Most shutouts in one month (six in 97-98)
* First European goalie to lead in GAA in one year (1993-94)
* First goalie since 1974 to have a GAA below 2.00 (1993-94)
</div><div style="float:left;">
{{h4|Playoffs}}
* 2nd place — Most shutouts in one<br>playoff season (6)
* 4th place — Most wins (57)
* 7th place (tied) — Most shutouts (12)

</div><br clear="all">

